definition: Fruitful; copious; abundant; plentiful.
One of a school of Lutheran divines which held that the body of Christ is present everywhere, and especially in the eucharist, in virtue of his omnipresence. Called also ubiquitist, and ubiquitary.
Quality or state of being ubiquitary, or ubiquitous.
Existing or being everywhere, or in all places, at the same time; omnipresent.
The doctrine, as formulated by Luther, that Christ's glorified body is omnipresent.

One of a sect of rigid Anabaptists, which originated in 1637, and whose tenets were essentially the same as those of the Mennonists. In addition, however, they held that Judas and the murderers of Christ were saved. So called from the founder of the sect, Ucke Wallis, a native of Friesland.
Allodial; -- a term used in Finland, Shetland, and Orkney. See Allodial.
One of the breasts of a woman.
Destitute or deprived of an udder.
Hence, without mother's milk; motherless; as, udderless lambs.
An exclamation expressive of disgust, horror, or recoil. Its utterance is usually accompanied by a shudder.
The quality or state of being ugly.
Offensive to the sight; contrary to beauty; being of disagreeable or loathsome aspect; unsightly; repulsive; deformed.
One of a kind of light cavalry of Tartaric origin, first introduced into European armies in Poland.  They are armed with lances, pistols, and sabers, and are employed chiefly as skirmishers.
In Russia, a published proclamation or imperial order, having the force of law.
A large East Indian nocturnal tree snake (Dipsas dendrophila). It is not venomous.

A solution of continuity in any of the soft parts of the body, discharging purulent matter, found on a surface, especially one of the natural surfaces of the body, and originating generally in a constitutional disorder; a sore discharging pus. It is distinguished from an abscess, which has its beginning, at least, in the depth of the tissues.
Fig.: Anything that festers and corrupts like an open sore; a vice in character.
To be formed into an ulcer; to become ulcerous.
To affect with, or as with, an ulcer or ulcers.
The process of forming an ulcer, or of becoming ulcerous; the state of being ulcerated; also, an ulcer.
Of or pertaining to ulcers; as, an ulcerative process.
Having the nature or character of an ulcer; discharging purulent or other matter.
Affected with an ulcer or ulcers; ulcerated.
A Mexican and Central American tree (Castilloa elastica and C. Markhamiana) related to the breadfruit tree. Its milky juice contains caoutchouc. Called also ule tree.
A college or corporation in Turkey composed of the hierarchy, namely, the imams, or ministers of religion, the muftis, or doctors of law, and the cadis, or administrators of justice.
A mineral occurring in white rounded crystalline masses. It is a hydrous borate of lime and soda.
Muddy; oozy; slimy; also, growing in muddy places.
A European owl (Syrnium aluco) of a tawny color; -- called also uluia.
A brittle mineral of a steel-gray color and metallic luster, containing antimony, arsenic, sulphur, and nickel.
Of or pertaining to a suborder of urticaceous plants, of which the elm is the type.
A salt of ulmic acid.
Pertaining to ulmin; designating an acid obtained from ulmin.
A brown amorphous substance found in decaying vegetation. Cf. Humin.
A genus of trees including the elm.
The postaxial bone of the forearm, or branchium, corresponding to the fibula of the hind limb. See Radius.
An ell; also, a yard.
Of or pertaining to the ulna, or the elbow; as, the ulnar nerve.
One of the bones or cartilages of the carpus, which articulates with the ulna and corresponds to the cuneiform in man.
A genus of fossil trees.
A division of insects nearly equivalent to the true Orthoptera.
Of or pertaining to the Ulotrichi.
The division of mankind which embraces the races having woolly or crispy hair. Cf. Leiotrichi.
Having woolly or crispy hair; -- opposed to leiotrichous.
A long, loose overcoat, worn by men and women, originally made of frieze from Ulster, Ireland.
Situated beyond, or on the farther side; thither; -- correlative with hither.
Further; remoter; more distant; succeeding; as, ulterior demands or propositions; ulterior views; what ulterior measures will be adopted is uncertain.
Most remote; furthest; final; last.
Farthest; most remote in space or time; extreme; last; final.
To come or bring into use or practice.
State of being ultimate; that which is ultimate, or final; ultimatum.
The act of taking vengeance; revenge.
Going beyond others, or beyond due limit; extreme; fanatical; uncompromising; as, an ultra reformer; ultra measures.
One who advocates extreme measures; an ultraist; an extremist; a radical.
The principles of those who advocate extreme measures, as radical reform, and the like.
Situated or being beyond the sea.
One who maintains extreme views favoring the pope's supremacy. See Ultramontanism.
One who upholds ultramontanism.
Being beyond the world, or beyond the limits of our system.
Situated beyond, or outside of, the tropics; extratropical; also, having an excessively tropical temperature; warmer than the tropics.
Lying outside the visible spectrum at its violet end; -- said of rays more refrangible than the extreme violet rays of the spectrum.
Beyond power; transcending authority; -- a phrase used frequently in relation to acts or enactments by corporations in excess of their chartered or statutory rights.

Outside the zodiac; being in that part of the heavens that is more than eight degrees from the ecliptic; as, ultrazodiacal planets, that is, those planets which in part of their orbits go beyond the zodiac.
A genus of owls including the great gray owl (Ulula cinerea) of Arctic America, and other similar species. See Illust. of Owl.
To howl, as a dog or a wolf; to wail; as, ululating jackals.
Of or pertaining to an umbel; having the form of an umbel.
Bearing umbels; pertaining to an umbel; umbel-like; as, umbellate plants or flowers.
A small or partial umbel; an umbellule.
Pertaining to, or obtained from, certain umbelliferous plants; as, umbellic acid.

A tasteless white crystalline substance, C9H6O3, found in the bark of a certain plant (Daphne Mezereum), and also obtained by the distillation of certain gums from the Umbellifer\'91, as galbanum, asafetida, etc. It is analogous to coumarin. Called also hydroxy-coumarin.
A genus of deep-sea alcyonaria consisting of a cluster of large flowerlike polyps situated at the summit of a long, slender stem which stands upright in the mud, supported by a bulbous base.

A brown or reddish pigment used in both oil and water colors, obtained from certain natural clays variously colored by the oxides of iron and manganese. It is commonly heated or burned before being used, and is then called burnt umber; when not heated, it is called raw umber. See Burnt umber, below.
The navel; the center.
An umbilicus. See Umbilicus, 5 (b).
Of or pertaining to an umbilicus, or umbilical cord; umbilic.
Pertaining to the center; central.
A slight, navel-like depression, or dimpling, of the center of a rounded body; as, the umbilication of a smallpox vesicle; also, the condition of being umbilicated.
The depression, or mark, in the median line of the abdomen, which indicates the point where the umbilical cord separated from the fetus; the navel.
An ornamented or painted ball or boss fastened at each end of the stick on which manuscripts were rolled.
The entrails and coarser parts of a deer; hence, sometimes, entrails, in general.
A boss, or rounded elevation, or a corresponding depression, in a palate, disk, or membrane; as, the umbo in the integument of the larv\'91 of echinoderms or in the tympanic membrane of the ear.

The conical shadow projected from a planet or satellite, on the side opposite to the sun, within which a spectator could see no portion of the sun's disk; -- used in contradistinction from penumbra. See Penumbra.

Any one of several species of sci\'91noid food fishes of the genus Umbrina, especially the Mediterranean species (U. cirrhosa), which is highly esteemed as a market fish; -- called also ombre, and umbrine.
Having the form of anything that serves to shade, as a tree top, an umbrella, and the like; specifically (Bot.), having the form of an umbrella; umbrella-shaped.
Of or pertaining to the shade or darkness; shadowy; unreal; secluded; retired.
The umbrellalike disk, or swimming bell, of a jellyfish.
Casting or making a shade; umbrageous.
The quality or state of being umbrose; shadiness.
The euphonic modification of a root vowel sound by the influence of a, u, or especially i, in the syllable which formerly followed.
The act of umpiring; arbitrament.

A person to whose sole decision a controversy or question between parties is referred; especially, one chosen to see that the rules of a game, as cricket, baseball, or the like, are strictly observed.
To perform the duties of umpire in or for; as, to umpire a game.
Un- is prefixed to adjectives, or to words used adjectively.

Not able; not having sufficient strength, means, knowledge, skill, or the like; impotent' weak; helpless; incapable; -- now usually followed by an infinitive or an adverbial phrase; as, unable for work; unable to bear fatigue.
Not absorbable; specifically (Physiol.), not capable of absorption; unable to pass by osmosis into the circulating blood; as, the unabsorbable portion of food.
The quality of being unacceptable; unacceptableness.
Not acceptable; not pleasing; not welcome; unpleasant; disagreeable; displeasing; offensive.
The state of being unaccomplished.
Not accountable or responsible; free from control.
Not to be accounted for; inexplicable; not consonant with reason or rule; strange; mysterious.
Not usual; uncommon; strange; new.
Not usual; unfamiliar; strange.
Not advisable; inadvisable; inexpedient.
Not prudent; not discreet; ill advised.
Done without due consideration; wanton; rash; inconsiderate; as, an unadvised proceeding.
Not agreeing or consistent; unsuitable.
An ecclesiastical who holds but one benefice; -- distinguished from pluralist.
Not alloyed; not reduced by foreign admixture; unmixed; unqualified; pure; as, unalloyed metals; unalloyed happiness.
The absence of ambition.
Not amiable; morose; ill-natured; repulsive.
To loose from the anchor, as a ship.
The quality or state of being unanimous.
Being of one mind; agreeing in opinion, design, or determination; consentient; not discordant or dissentient; harmonious; as, the assembly was unanimous; the members of the council were unanimous.
Formed with unanimity; indicating unanimity; having the agreement and consent of all; agreed upon without the opposition or contradiction of any; as, a unanimous opinion; a unanimous vote.
Not answerable; irrefutable; conclusive; decisive; as, he have an unanswerable argument.
Not answered; not replied; as, an unanswered letter.
Not refuted; as, an unanswered argument.
Not to be appealed from; -- said of a judge or a judgment that can not be overruled.
Not granted to any person, corporation, or the like, to the exclusion of others; as, unappropriated lands.
Not argued against; undisputed.
Not armed or armored; having no arms or weapons.
Not artificial; plain; simple.
Not assuming; not bold or forward; not arrogant or presuming; humble; modest; retiring; as, an unassuming youth; unassuming manners.
Not assured; not bold or confident.
Not to be trusted.
Incapable of being atoned for; inexpiable.
Not assigned to any company or regiment.
To divest of attire; to undress.
The two-toed sloth (Cholopus didactylus), native of South America. It is about two feet long. Its color is a uniform grayish brown, sometimes with a reddish tint.
Not given an audience; not received or heard.
Not avoidable; incapable of being shunned or prevented; inevitable; necessary; as, unavoidable troubles.
Not voidable; incapable of being made null or void.
Not supported or encouraged; not countenanced; unaided.
Not balanced; not in equipoise; having no counterpoise, or having insufficient counterpoise.
Not adjusted; not settled; not brought to an equality of debt and credit; as, an unbalanced account; unbalanced books.
Not furnished with ballast; not kept steady by ballast; unsteady; as, unballasted vessels; unballasted wits.
Destitute of bards, or of reversed points, hairs, or plumes; as, an unbarded feather.
To unbolt; to unbar; to open.
To deliver from the form or nature of a beast.
To deliver from the state of a fool; to awaken the mind of; to undeceive.
To deprive of existence.
Not begot; not yet generated; also, having never been generated; self-existent; eternal.
To set free from the influence of guile; to undeceive.
Not behooving or becoming; unseemly.
The withholding of belief; doubt; incredulity; skepticism.
Disbelief; especially, disbelief of divine revelation, or in a divine providence or scheme of redemption.
One who does not believe; an incredulous person; a doubter; a skeptic.
A disbeliever; especially, one who does not believe that the Bible is a divine revelation, and holds that Christ was neither a divine nor a supernatural person; an infidel; a freethinker.
To free from flexure; to make, or allow to become, straight; to loosen; as, to unbend a bow.
A remit from a strain or from exertion; to set at ease for a time; to relax; as, to unbend the mind from study or care.
To relax in exertion, attention, severity, or the like; hence, to indulge in mirth or amusement.
Not bending; not suffering flexure; not yielding to pressure; stiff; -- applied to material things.
To relieve of numbness; to restore sensation to.
Not bereft; not taken away.
To be unbecoming or unsuitable to; to misbecome.
To unsay; hence, to annul or cancel.
Not bidden; not commanded.
To deprive, as a city, of a bishop; to deprive, as a clergyman, of episcopal dignity or rights.
To free from the body; to disembody.
To deprive of bones, as meat; to bone.
Not born; no yet brought into life; being still to appear; future.
To disclose freely; to reveal in confidence, as secrets; to confess; -- often used reflexively; as, to unbosom one's self.
Having no bottom; bottomless.
To divest of the traits of a boy.
To disclose, or lay open; to unbosom.
Not taught or trained; -- with to.
To free the breech of, as a cannon, from its fastenings or coverings.
Loosed from the bridle, or as from the bridle; hence, unrestrained; licentious; violent; as, unbridled passions.
To loose the buckles of; to unfasten; as, to unbuckle a shoe.
To remove the bung from; as, to unbung a cask.
To relieve from a burden.
To throw off, as a burden; to unload.
To unburden; to unload.
To disinter; to exhume; fig., to disclose.
Not required to work; unemployed; not busy.
To loose, or release, from, or as from, a cage.
Not called for; not required or needed; improper; gratuitous; wanton.
To disturb; to disquiet.
To reduce from the rank of a canonized saint.
An instrument for removing an explode cap from a cartridge shell.
To degrade from the cardinalship.
Not cared for; not heeded; -- with for.
Not fleshy; specifically, not made flesh; not incarnate.
To take from, or set free from, a cart; to unload.
To take out of a case or covering; to remove a case or covering from; to uncover.
Having no antecedent cause; uncreated; self-existent; eternal.
An ounce; a small portion.
To throw from its center.
To remove from its actual century.
The quality or state of being uncertain.
To free from chains or slavery; to let loose.
To free from a charge or load; to unload.
The quality or state of being unchaste; lewdness; incontinence.
Not capable of being checked or stopped.
To bereave of children; to make childless.
Not Christian; not converted to the Christian faith; infidel.
Contrary to Christianity; not like or becoming a Christian; as, unchristian conduct.
The quality or state of being unchristian.
To deprive of the character, privileges, and authority of a church.
A numerical coefficient in any particular case of the binomial theorem.
Having the shape of a hook; being of a curved or hooked from; hooklike.
A division of marine ch\'91topod annelids which are furnished with uncini, as the serpulas and sabellas.
Hooked; bent at the tip in the form of a hook; as, an uncinate process.
One of the peculiar minute chitinous hooks found in large numbers in the tori of tubicolous annelids belonging to the Uncinata.
To decipher; as, to uncipher a letter.
People not circumcised; the Gentiles.
Not important; not pertinent; trivial.
Not civilized; savage; barbarous; uncivilized.
Not civil; not complaisant; discourteous; impolite; rude; unpolished; as, uncivil behavior.
The state of being uncivilized; savagery or barbarism.
Not civilized; not reclaimed from savage life; rude; barbarous; savage; as, the uncivilized inhabitants of Central Africa.
Not civil; coarse; clownish.
To loose the clasp of; to open, as something that is fastened, or as with, a clasp; as, to unclasp a book; to unclasp one's heart.
The brother of one's father or mother; also applied to an aunt's husband; -- the correlative of aunt in sex, and of nephew and niece in relationship.
Ceremonially impure; needing ritual cleansing.
The office or position of an uncle.
To cease from clinging or adhering.
To remove, or take off, one's cloak.
To disencumber of a clog, or of difficulties and obstructions; to free from encumbrances; to set at liberty.
To open; to separate the parts of; as, to unclose a letter; to unclose one's eyes.
To disclose; to lay open; to reveal.
Not separated by inclosures; open.
Not yet clothed; wanting clothes; naked.
To open, as something closely shut.
In a high degree; to a great extent; greatly; very.
A strange thing or person.
To detach or loose from a coach.
To deprive of its cocked shape, as a hat, etc.
To deprive of the coif or cap.
Not fabricated; not artificial or counterfeit; natural.
Causing discomfort; disagreeable; unpleasant; as, an uncomfortable seat or situation.
Want of concern; absence of anxiety; freedom from solicitude; indifference.
Not conditional limited, or conditioned; made without condition; absolute; unreserved; as, an unconditional surrender.
Not subject to condition or limitations; infinite; absolute; hence, inconceivable; incogitable.
Want of parallelism between one series of strata and another, especially when due to a disturbance of the position of the earlier strata before the latter were deposited.
Not conformable; not lying in a parallel position; as, unconformable strata.
Want of conformity; incongruity; inconsistency.
Want of parallelism between strata in contact.
Not conscionable; not conforming to reason; unreasonable; exceeding the limits of any reasonable claim or expectation; inordinate; as, an unconscionable person or demand; unconscionable size.
Not known or apprehended by consciousness; as, an unconscious cerebration.
Not constitutional; not according to, or consistent with, the terms of a constitution of government; contrary to the constitution; as, an unconstitutional law, or act of an officer.
Freedom from constraint; ease.
Indisputable; irrefragable; as, an uncontrollable maxim; an uncontrollable title.
Not converted or exchanged.
Not changed in opinion, or from one faith to another.
To draw the cork from; as, to uncork a bottle.
To loose, as dogs, from their couples; also, to set loose; to disconnect; to disjoin; as, to uncouple railroad cars.
To roam at liberty.
Not having joined in a league, or assented to a covenant or agreement, as to the Solemn League and Covenant of the Scottish people in the times of the Stuarts.
To show openly; to disclose; to reveal.
To remove the covers from dishes, or the like.
Deprived of existence; annihilated.
To deprive of a crown; to take the crown from; hence, to discrown; to dethrone.
Quality or state of being unctuous.
Having a smooth, greasy feel, as certain minerals.
In an uncurable manner.
Not capable of being curbed.
Not current. Specifically: Not passing in common payment; not receivable at par or full value; as, uncurrent notes.
Not customable, or subject to custom duties.
Uncustomable; also, not having paid duty or customs.
Not ground, or otherwise cut, into a certain shape; as, an uncut diamond.
To free from a dam, mound, or other obstruction.
Not dated; having no date; of unknown age; as, an undated letter.
Incapable of being daunted; intrepid; fearless; indomitable.
Not subject to death; immortal.
A liquid hydrocarbon, C11H24, of the methane series, found in petroleum; -- so called from its containing eleven carbon atoms in the molecule.
To cause to be no longer deceived; to free from deception, fraud, fallacy, or mistake.
To reverse or recant, as a previous decision.
Not having a deck; as, an undecked vessel.
Reversed or nullified by decree, as something previously decreed.
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid C11H20O2, homologous with acrylic acid, and obtained as a white crystalline substance by the distillation of castor oil.
Related to, derived from, or containing, undecyl; specifically, designating that member of the fatty acids which corresponds to undecane, and is obtained as a white crystalline substance, C11H22O2.
Not deeded or transferred by deed; as, undeeded land.
Not made famous by any great action.
To make indefinite; to obliterate or confuse the definition or limitations of.
To degrade from the state of deity; to deprive of the character or qualities of a god; to deprive of the reverence due to a god.
Unobjectionable; unquestionably excellent; as, a person of undeniable connections.
Incapable of being parted; inseparable.
Subordinate action; a minor action incidental or subsidiary to the main story; an episode.
Not having arrived at adult age, or at years of discretion; hence, raw; green; immature; boyish; childish.
Done (as bowling) with the arm not raised above the elbow, that is, not swung far out from the body; underhand. Cf. Over-arm and Round-Arm.
A vessel which receives the wort as it flows from the mashing tub.
To support; to endure.
To line; to guard; to face; as, cloth of gold underborne with blue tinsel.
To bid less than, as when a contract or service is offered to the lowest bidder; to offer to contract, sell, or do for a less price than.
To brace, fasten, or bind underneath or below.
A twig or branchlet.
A subordinate or assistant builder.
To buy at less than the real value or worth; to buy cheaper than.
A deputy chamberlain of the exchequer.
The lower chaps or jaw.
To put too small a charge into; as, to undercharge a gun.
A stratum of clay lying beneath a coal bed, often containing the roots of coal plants, especially the Stigmaria.
A subordinate cliff on a shore, consisting of material that has fallen from the higher cliff above.
Clothes worn under others, especially those worn next the skin for warmth.
A coat worn under another; a light coat, as distinguished from an overcoat, or a greatcoat.
A growth of short hair or fur partially concealed by a longer growth; as, a dog's undercoat.

Hence, figuratively, a tendency of feeling, opinion, or the like, in a direction contrary to what is publicly shown; an unseen influence or tendency; as, a strong undercurrent of sentiment in favor of a prisoner.
To cut away, as the side of an object, so as to leave an overhanging portion.
Crafty, unfair, or underhand dealing; unfair practice; trickery.
To dig under or beneath; to undermine.
To do less than is requisite or proper; -- opposed to overdo.
One who underdoes; a shirk.
p. p. of Underdelve.
A dose which is less than required; a small or insufficient dose.
To give an underdose or underdoses to; to practice giving insufficient doses.
An underground drain or trench with openings through which the water may percolate from the soil or ground above.
To drain by forming an underdrain or underdrains in; as, to underdrain land.
To set to<?/ low a value on; to estimate below the truth.
The act of underestimating; too low an estimate.
A subordinate party or faction.
An inferior or subordinate faculty.
To feed with too little food; to supply with an insufficient quantity of food.
An underling <?/<?/ mean, low fellow.
To insnare; to circumvent.
Low; base; abject; trodden down.
A lower fringe; a fringe underneath something.
A garment worn below another.
To get under or beneath; also, to understand.
To go or move below or under.

To be subjected to; to bear up against; to pass through; to endure; to suffer; to sustain; as, to undergo toil and fatigue; to undergo pain, grief, or anxiety; to undergothe operation of amputation; food in the stomach undergoes the process of digestion.
A gown worn under another, or under some other article of dress.
Of or pertaining to an undergraduate, or the body of undergraduates.
The position or condition of an undergraduate.
Done or occurring out of sight; secret.
A grove of shrubs or low trees under taller ones.
That which grows under trees; specifically, shrubs or small trees growing among large trees.
Done, as pitching, with the hand lower than the shoulder, or, as bowling, with the hand lower than elbow.
To hang under or down; to suspend.
Having the lower jaw projecting.
To lay beneath; to put under.
To raise or support by something laid under; as, to underlay a cut, plate, or the like, for printing. See Underlay, n., 2.
The inclination of a vein, fault, or lode from the vertical; a hade; -- called also underlie.

A thickness of paper, pasteboard, or the like, placed under a cut, or stereotype plate, or under type, in the from, to bring it, or any part of it, to the proper height; also, something placed back of a part of the tympan, so as to secure the right impression.

To let or lease at second hand; to sublet.

A lock of wool hanging under the belly of a sheep.
A person who inspects a mine daily; -- called also underviewer.
Lying under or beneath; hence, fundamental; as, the underlying strata of a locality; underlying principles.
Insufficiently furnished with men; short-handed.
Having masts smaller than the usual dimension; -- said of vessels.
One who is not a match for another.
Hence, something occurring or done in the afternoon; esp., an afternoon meal; supper; also, an afternoon nap; a siesta.

To receive; to perceive.

A series of events in a play, proceeding collaterally with the main story, and subservient to it.

To undervalue; to underestimate.

To put or send under.

Inadequately equipped with sails.
Not fully saturated; imperfectly saturated.
To say by way of derogation or contradiction.
To sell the same articles at a lower price than; to sell cheaper than.
To prop or support.

Something set or built under as a support; a pedestal.
A shirt worn next the skin, under another shirt; -- called also undervest.
To shoot short of (a mark).
Having the lower incisor teeth projecting beyond the upper ones, as in the bulldog.
Moved by water passing beneath; -- said of a water wheel, and opposed to overshot; as, an undershot wheel.

The lower region of the sky.

The basement or cellar.

Suture of the palate. See Staphyloraphy.

An order of amphibians having the tail well developed and often long. It comprises the salamanders, tritons, and allied animals.
One of the Urodela.

Behind the stomach; -- said of two lobes of the carapace of certain crustaceans.

Urinary h\'91matin; -- applied to the normal coloring matter of the urine, on the supposition that it is formed either directly or indirectly (through bilirubin) from the h\'91matin of the blood. See Urochrome, and Urobilin.

Pertaining to, or designating, an acid, C5H8N4O6, which is obtained, as a white crystalline substance, by the slow oxidation of uric acid in alkaline solution.

A beautiful North American butterfly (Basilarchia, ∨ Limenitis, astyanax). Its wings are nearly black with red and blue spots and blotches. Called also red-spotted purple.

One of an order of nuns founded by St. Angela Merici, at Brescia, in Italy, about the year 1537, and so called from St. Ursula, under whose protection it was placed. The order was introduced into Canada as early as 1639, and into the United States in 1727. The members are devoted entirely to education.
Of or pertaining to St. Ursula, or the order of Ursulines; as, the Ursuline nuns.
A genus of Carnivora including the common bears.
